<BaseLayout title={title} description={description}>
  <section class="card card-pad prose prose-slate max-w-none">
    <h1>How to measure flour correctly</h1>
    <p>Flour is the most common source of recipe inconsistency. The difference between a light, spooned cup and a compact, scooped cup can be 20–30% of the total flour weight. That gap is enough to turn a tender cake into a dense one or a chewy cookie into a dry crumb. The goal is not to obsess over perfection but to reduce surprise. A consistent method gives consistent results.</p>
    <p>The most reliable approach is a kitchen scale. Weighing bypasses packing and humidity variables. When a recipe calls for cups, you can still translate to grams with known densities. For example, a level cup of all-purpose flour typically weighs around 125 g, while a cup of bread flour is slightly heavier. You can explore those differences on the conversion pages for <a href="/cooking/all-purpose-flour/cup-to-g/">all‑purpose flour</a> and <a href="/cooking/bread-flour/cup-to-g/">bread flour</a>.</p>
    <p>If you are using cups, use the spoon-and-level method. Fluff the flour, spoon it into the cup without shaking, and level with a straight edge. Avoid packing the flour with a scoop or tapping the cup on the counter. Those actions can add many grams without you realizing it. Sifting helps when you need a lighter texture, but it also reduces weight per cup, which is why sifted flour has its own density.</p>
    <p>Different flours behave differently. Cake flour is milled finer and contains less protein, so it sits lighter in a cup. Whole wheat flour has more bran and germ, which makes it heavier. A single measuring technique applied across flours still produces different weights, so it’s useful to check the specific conversion page for the flour you are using.</p>
    <p>Humidity matters too. Flour absorbs moisture from the air, which raises its weight slightly. The effect is smaller than the scoop-versus-spoon difference, but it can add up over many cups. If you bake often, store flour in an airtight container and allow it to acclimate to your kitchen before measuring. Consistency is more valuable than a theoretical “perfect” number.</p>
    <p>When recipes specify “sifted flour,” it usually means you should sift after measuring by volume. This matters because sifting can reduce the density by as much as 10–15%. If the recipe author is expecting that lighter flour and you scoop directly from the bag, the dough will be too dry. See the conversions for <a href="/ingredients/all-purpose-flour-sifted/">sifted all‑purpose flour</a> and <a href="/ingredients/all-purpose-flour-scooped/">scooped all‑purpose flour</a> for the range.</p>
    <p>For quick conversions in a pinch, use tablespoons or teaspoons. Small measures are easier to level consistently, and the error is smaller. A tablespoon of flour varies less in absolute grams than a full cup. You can calculate from the <a href="/cooking/all-purpose-flour/tbsp-to-g/">tablespoon conversion</a> if you need to scale or troubleshoot a recipe.</p>
    <p>Ultimately, the best approach is to pick a method and stick with it. If you always spoon and level, you will learn how your recipes behave. If you always weigh, you’ll get the same output every time. The goal for Numericano is to give you a reference point so you can keep your results predictable.</p>
    <p>Use flour conversions as a guide, not a strict rule. Different brands and milling styles can vary. Start with a typical density, then adjust based on how the dough or batter feels. A consistent system turns “close enough” into reliable.</p>
  </section>

  <section class="card card-pad mt-6">
    <h2 class="text-lg font-bold mb-3">FAQ</h2>
    <div class="space-y-2">
      <details class="rounded-xl border border-slate-200 p-3">
        <summary class="cursor-pointer font-semibold text-slate-900">Why does my cup of flour weigh more than the chart?</summary>
        <p class="mt-2 text-slate-700">Most charts assume a spoon-and-level cup. Scooping directly from the bag compresses flour and increases the weight. Try aerating the flour and leveling gently.</p>
      </details>
      <details class="rounded-xl border border-slate-200 p-3">
        <summary class="cursor-pointer font-semibold text-slate-900">Do I need to sift every time?</summary>
        <p class="mt-2 text-slate-700">Only when the recipe specifically calls for sifted flour or when you need an especially light texture. Sifting changes density, so measure first, then sift.</p>
      </details>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
